Rafe tensed. Matthis clenched his jaw. The skeletons did not stumble or wander. Shoulder to shoulder, they stepped around Matthis and Rafe. Rafe exhaled. Matthis narrowed his eyes.

Each deliberate step touched the mud without a squelch and lifted again without a stain. Pristine, white bones drifted through the square. A group of children playing a game in an alley halted the game. Their leather ball fell. Their faces paled. They scurried away like roaches from light and peeked around corners and through door cracks. The skeletons did not stop or react. Empty sockets forward, they proceeded one step after another. The street echoed Matthis's and Rafe's footsteps. 

One man in a dusty black cap emerged onto a narrow street with his pickaxe slung behind his neck, the flat end curled around his shoulder and tucked safely into his armpit. In a single file, the skeletons drifted around him. The man jumped and swung his pickaxe. The skeleton nearest him exploded. He dropped the haft from shaky hands. He backed away and stumbled into a wall. Rafe laid a hand on the man's shoulder. The struck skeleton lay in bone fragments scattered across the dirt street. The others did not break stride. They simply split around the pair, like water around rocks.

Matthis gasped. The fragments reassembled themselves. He stopped to watch. Rafe stood beside him. Pieces flew through the air and reattached themselves. Joints locked into place. Ribs slipped into the spine. The complete skeleton resumed its silent march as though nothing had happened. Rafe and Matthis looked at each other. The man, his mouth open, pulled his pickaxe out of the mud. Not a single skull moved to look back. 

The skeletons glided around a corner past the carpenter's shop. Through a window, Matthis spotted Mercy talking to the carpenter's wife. Mercy halted her conversation. Her eyebrows rose. She bared her teeth. She rushed to the shop door and flung it open. She watched the procession slide up the street. Matthis locked eyes with her. She glowered. He looked away.

The shop long behind them, Matthis checked over his shoulder and surveyed the street. Mercy stalked them, her eyes shadowed. She whispered to anyone who poked a head around their doors or windows. A group slowly formed around her. Several scowled at Matthis. One man bared his brown teeth. Matthis saw the flash of kitchen knives. Many carried pickaxes.  

Heads ducked out of windows and doors, which slammed shut. A woman with a baby in her arms squeaked and rushed to cover her child with her body and scrambled around a corner. Three men outside the apothecary fell to their knees. 

A man in a spotless, dustless white robe, whom Matthis had never seen, sat atop a sleek, muscular horse and spoke to Bartholomew and Godric. The man's head snapped forward and watched the procession, arms folded and resting on the horse's neck, face hard. Bartholomew gaped, and his arms circled his middle. Godric steadied himself on a wall.

Nine skeletons crested the cemetery hill, followed by Matthis and Rafe. A group trailed behind them, headed by Mercy. A dull glint shone from gray headstones, once coal-dusted, now rain-washed. 

The shadow of Blackvein peak sliced the cemetery hill in two. Eight skeletons stood in the light. Mercy and her mob glared from the shadow. Matthis saw the white-robed man still on his horse at the bottom of the hill. 

For a moment, sunlight blinded Matthis in one eye, and shadow obscured the other. Not one sound or movement disturbed the breathless mob on one side, the blank, motionless skeletons on the other. Not even the black skeleton moaned. Grass shifted in a silent breeze. Goodman Morrel's fresh grave still smelled ancient, disturbed. Not even birds sang.

 Still cut in half by sun and shade, Matthis looked between the skeletons and the mob. Matthis stepped into the light. Whispers from the shadow prickled down his spine. "Bone Man. Bone Man. Bone Man." 

Dark lines still connected him with many of the skeletons. He felt a slight tug along each one, and five white skeletons moved between the graves. One of the five had no black line attached to it. 

One by one, each of the five found its own patch of cemetery grass and stood there. Each of them faced a wooden or stone marker. Matthis recognized those graves. He remembered the way the fresh soil had lain, as though cracked from beneath the surface, like the burrow of an enormous creature. The same bodies that had once clawed and scratched out of their graves stood upon the same soil now. One of them knelt and touched the faded name scratched into the wooden head marker. It had no black line attached to it. 

A strangled cry ripped the crowd in two. Men hefted their pickaxes and swung around, looking for the one who yelled. Then the crowd parted. A woman wrapped in a tattered shawl and filthy apron pushed through the crowd. When she tried to push past Mercy, she stopped. The woman trembled. From anger, grief, or weakness, Matthis couldn't tell.

"That's my Kendrick's grave!" the woman shouted. "What is that ... that thing doing to Kendrick's grave!" 

"After all this time," Rafe whispered, "they still don't understand what you do for them."

Matthis faced the woman. He squared his shoulders. He ignored Rafe's gestures. He refused to dominate these people. The woman's eyes were red and stretched. He met her gaze and didn't flinch. He opened his mouth. Nothing came out. He closed it again. 

"He didn't even know your husband's name, Maud." Mercy's voice chilled the hill like ice. "The monster took him from the grave, kept him in a cage, and he doesn't even remember his name."

Rafe clenched his fists. "They think you did this?" 

Maud was crying. Mercy balled her fists in her apron. Murder flashed in one man's eyes as he wrapped a cloth around his knuckles. Fingers whitened around the handle of a kitchen knife. One man had both hands on his pickaxe and looked ready to swing and throw it over his head. Rafe raised his head, teeth bared. Matthis moved to stop him from speaking. 

All movement stopped. A skeleton drifted around Matthis and Rafe. But it didn't look like Kendrick's skeleton anymore. Perhaps a trick of the light deceived them all. Perhaps the intensity of the moment caused a hallucination. But every eye saw the same thing. 

Kendrick, with all his flesh and clothing restored, floated across the divide of light and shadow. 

He wore typical miner's clothing, black boots, thick smock, heavy trousers. They were dusty. His hands were smoother than a normal miner, the hands of a wizard. A gray beard reached his chest, thick and full. His hands engulfed Maud's. Mouth open, she just stared and let Kendrick take her hand. Matthis saw her fingers pass through Kendrick's flesh and touch white bone. Kendrick's beard lifted. He was smiling at her. 

Everyone watched. Mercy's hand was at her throat, her eyes wide. Weapons dropped to the ground. The man who had murder in his eyes placed a hand over his mouth. 

Kendrick led his wife back to his grave. As if in a trance, she followed, her tiny hand in his. In the sunlight, Kendrick's image faded, like water draining from cupped hands. A skeleton once more, Kendrick lay upon his grave. Maud's hands still entwined with his, he folded his hands on his chest. She knelt beside him. His skull turned toward her. 

"Handsome as the day we met," she whispered.

Kendrick lifted his arm and beckoned to Matthis. Matthis gaped. He looked at Rafe, who shrugged. 

The steps he took to reach Kendrick's side felt longer than the path from the gallows to the grave. He knelt beside the skeleton across from Maud. She looked at him. Her eyes were still red. But she smiled. 

Maud held one hand. Matthis held the other. Kendrick gripped them both tightly to his chest. For another moment, Matthis saw the true Kendrick again. His eyes were screwed up in fear. He clung to Maud and Matthis's hands like a child. 

Matthis didn't think. He laid his other hand on Kendrick's forehead, gray and thinning. Kendrick's lips trembled. Warmth flowers through Matthis. Not all of it was magic. 

Peace. 

Kendrick's face relaxed. His grip loosened. A tear tricked from both eyes. His arms stopped trembling. His image faded. His white bones dissolved to dust. Maud wept quietly. But she smiled. 

"He can rest now," she said. She didn't wipe her tears. They fell on Kendrick's dust, the last of which glittered in the sunlight and settled back to the grave.